  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">STAR Call 1- Engaging the Security Agencies for peaceful Elections in 2016</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Both anecdotal and empirical evidences point to the fact that there are always incidence of brutalities meted out to the voting public by the security agencies during the process of casting their ballot. This behaviour of the security agencies tend to intimidate the voting public, leading in some instances to some of them not even willing to go out to cast their ballot, thereby denying them their right and responsibility to vote as citizens. Security agencies therefore need to be sensitised/educated/trained not only on the laws on Election &#x2013; C.I 75 and other relevant laws, but also on the code of Ethics of elections. They being knowledgeable on the laws and code of conduct will minimize incidences of brutalisation and violence&apos;s during the exercise. Thus engendering voter confidence in the system and a fair, peaceful and credible elections. The Police has a responsibility to see to a fair and peaceful election The Electoral Commission also has a responsibility to organize a peaceful credible election in 2016. AWLA is therefore complementing them to consolidate their training which will be provided from a legal perspective.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The knowledge gained by the security forces leads to a change in their attitude towards the voting public during the 2016 elections. Both the voting public and the security agencies collaborate to ensure a fair, credible and peaceful 2016 elections. The voting citizenry exercise their right to vote in November 2016</narrative>
  </description>
